## Personal Reflection

This week's workshop helped me gain a much better understanding of artificial intelligence and how it is used in everyday life. Before attending the class, I thought AI simply meant computers that could think like humans. During the lecture and class discussions, I realised that AI does not actually think or understand information the way people do. Instead, AI analyses large amounts of data, identifies patterns, and predicts the most likely response based on what it has learned. This changed the way I think about artificial intelligence and helped me understand why AI can sometimes produce incorrect or biased answers.

One of the most enjoyable parts of the workshop was listening to the different opinions shared by my classmates. Everyone had a unique perspective on AI and how it is affecting society. Some students spoke about how AI makes studying easier by helping with research, writing, and problem-solving. Others discussed how businesses use AI to improve customer service and increase productivity. We also talked about the possible disadvantages of AI, including privacy concerns, biased decision-making, misinformation, and the impact AI may have on future employment. Hearing these different viewpoints helped me realise that AI is not only a technological innovation but also an ethical and social issue that affects many aspects of our daily lives.

Another topic that I found particularly interesting was the comparison between IBM Watson and ChatGPT. Before this workshop, I assumed that all AI systems worked in the same way. However, I learned that different AI systems are designed for different purposes. IBM Watson was developed to answer structured questions accurately and became famous after winning the quiz show *Jeopardy!*. In contrast, ChatGPT is designed to communicate naturally with users, generate text, answer questions, and assist with many different tasks. Comparing these two systems helped me understand that there is no single AI model that is best for every situation. Instead, each system has its own strengths depending on the problem it is designed to solve.

The workshop also introduced the importance of ethics in artificial intelligence. We discussed how AI systems can sometimes make mistakes because they depend on the quality of the data used during training. If the training data contains bias or errors, the AI may produce unfair or inaccurate results. This made me realise that people cannot rely entirely on AI without human judgement and oversight. Developers, organisations, and governments all have a responsibility to ensure that AI systems are transparent, fair, reliable, and used in ways that benefit society.

Overall, I found this workshop both interesting and informative. It expanded my understanding of artificial intelligence beyond simply using AI tools such as ChatGPT. I now have a greater appreciation of the history of AI, the different technologies that make AI possible, and the ethical responsibilities involved in developing and using these systems. The workshop has increased my curiosity about artificial intelligence, and I look forward to learning more about how AI will continue to shape education, business, healthcare, and society in the future. I also believe the knowledge gained in this workshop will be valuable for my future career as an ICT professional, where ethical decision-making will be just as important as technical skills.
